 This new evaluation of the n+12C reactions is based on a two-     625 1451
 channel R-matrix analysis of reactions in the 13C system at       625 1451
 energies up to 6.45 MeV.  The two channels included are for       625 1451
 neutron plus the ground state and first excited state of 12C.     625 1451
 Data included were total cross sections, elastic scattering       625 1451
 differential cross sections and analyzing powers, and dif-        625 1451
 ferential cross sections for inelastic scattering to the first    625 1451
 excited state (Ex=4.4389 MeV) of 12C.  A good fit (chi-square/    625 1451
 d.o.f. = 1.54) was obtained to the 7390 data points included in   625 1451
 the experimental data set.                                        625 1451
                                                                   625 1451
 At neutron energies above 6.45 MeV, the evaluation was joined     625 1451
 to the existing ENDF/B-VII.0 evaluation for natural carbon, which 625 1451
 is essentially version VI.1 (Fu, Axton, and Perey).  At these     625 1451
 energies, there are almost no effects coming from the minor       625 1451
 isotope, ~1.1% 13C, in elemental carbon.  The matching was done   625 1451
 in the range 6.4-6.5 MeV, and the changes required to do it were  625 1451
 minimal.  All cross sections were kept the same as the VII.0 file 625 1451
 in the energy range 6.47 <= E <= 20 MeV, except for the capture   625 1451
 cross section, as described below.  The version VI.3 extension    625 1451
 to 150 MeV (Chadwick and Young) was not retained in this file.    625 1451
                                                                   625 1451
 Results from the new R-matrix analysis were used to give the      625 1451
 elastic (3-2) and inelastic (3-51) cross sections at energies     625 1451
 below 6.47 MeV, as well as the Legendre coefficients for the      625 1451
 elastic (4-2) and inelastic (4-51) angular distributions in       625 1451
 this range.  There are fairly significant changes from the        625 1451
 previous evaluation for the Legendre coefficients, especially     625 1451
 near narrow resonances, but much less so for the integrated       625 1451
 cross sections, at most energies below 6.47 MeV.                  625 1451
                                                                   625 1451
 Another change is in the radiative capture cross section (3-102). 625 1451
 Following JENDL-4, we changed the thermal value to 3.86 mb to     625 1451
 agree with Firestone's 2007 evaluation of thermal capture cross   625 1451
 sections.  The fit also included the data of Ohsaki at energies   625 1451
 between 21 and 199 keV, so the deviation from 1/v behavior at low 625 1451
 energies could be determined.  The extrapolation of the cross     625 1451
 section from this calculation above 200 keV runs well above the   625 1451
 data of Cook, and joins smoothly with the previous evaluation at  625 1451
 about 7 MeV.  Thus, it is significantly higher than the JENDL-4   625 1451
 evaluation at energies between 0.5 and 10 MeV, which was based on 625 1451
 the Cook data.  These data, measured as 13C(gamma,n)12C, include  625 1451
 only the ground-state transition for 12C(n,gamma)13C, which the   625 1451
 Ohsaki measurement showed is less important than the excited-     625 1451
 state transitions as the energy increases.  Therefore the Cook    625 1451
 data can give only a lower limit for the total (n,gamma) cross    625 1451
 section at energies below the first excited state of 12C.         625 1451
